  <discussion>Like Corylus americana Walter, the beaked hazel (C. cornuta subsp. cornuta) is a weedy shrub and is sometimes considered a pest in carefully managed northern forests. The fruits are similar to those of C. americana, except that the surrounding bracts are connate into a long, narrow, tubular beak. Vegetative individuals of C. cornuta subsp. cornuta can be distinguished from C. americana by the absence of glandular hairs on the petioles and young twigs.</discussion>
